The state's requirement that write-in candidates' names must be written in ink by voters (rather than allowing pre-printed stickers) **unreasonably restricts freedom of speech** by imposing an undue burden on voters' ability to support a candidate, particularly those who may struggle with literacy or language barriers. This implicates the **First Amendment** because it limits how voters can effectively communicate their political preferences. The state's interpretation effectively penalizes candidates who rely on non-traditional (but constitutionally protected) campaign methods.
